questiontext.text:
This is the question type for C programming courses at the University of Canterbury. The following documents the template parameters that can be used to specify the behavior of questions using this question type.

Parameters:

  • abortonerror (bool): true to abort the test sequence if a runtime error occurs. Doesn't work (probably) if allowstderr is true. Default: true.
  • allowglobals (bool): if true, global variables are allowed in the student's answer. Default: false.
  • allowmodulestatics: (bool): if true, static variables are allowed in the students answer at the module level. Default: false.

  • allowpositivereturn (bool): if true, a positive return code from the program execution is silently ignored. Default: false.

  • allowstderr (bool): if true stderr output is not interpreted as a run time error, but is appended to stdout with a header to identify it as stderr. Default: false.

  • arrayregex (string): the regular expression that all array variable names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

  • checkheaderguard (bool): if true then all submitted '.h' files will be checked to ensure they have a header guard. Default: true.

  • checktemplateparams (bool): if true, template parameters not starting with '_' must be known to the prototype. Default: true.

  • constructlimits (JSON object/dictionary): a map from construct name ('for', 'while' etc) to the maximum number of such constructs that may appear in the program. Default: {}.

  • executablefilename (string): the name of the file to be executed. If using a Makefile, this must be the name of the generated executable. Otherwise, the gcc command will be configured to generate an executable file of this name. Default: student_answer

  • extra (string): how to use the testcase extra field. One of ['', 'pretest', 'posttest', 'stdin'].  Default ''. The case of 'stdin' is exactly equivalent to setting 'stdinfromextra' to true. The result of setting stdinfromextra to true and extra to anything other than either the empty string or 'stdin' is probably chaos. Except for the 'stdin' case, this parameter is ignored if isfunction is false.

  • flags (stringlist): A list of compile flags for the gcc command. To this is added "-o executablefilename". Default: ["-g", "--std=c99", "-Wall", "-Werror"]

  • includes (stringlist): a list of headers (including quotes/angle brackets, and .h, e.g. "<openmp.h>" or "local_test.h") that should be added to the top of the file if isfunction is true. Ignored otherwise. The list given by this parameter supplements the default set, which is

    • <stdio.h>
    • <stdlib.h>
    • <ctype.h>
    • <string.h>
    • <stdbool.h>
    • <math.h>

     

  • functionregex (string): the regular expression that all function names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

  • ldflags: (string list): a list of flags to go at the end of the gcc command. Default: ["-lm"]

  • isfunction (bool): if true, the question is only asking for a function, and the test cases are placed in a main function. Otherwise, the question is assumed to be a program and so should already contain a main function. Default false.

  • ignoreanswerbox (bool): if true what ever is entered into the answer box is ignored. Only test cases and uploaded files are used. Default: false.

  • mkflags (string list): a list of flags for use if usemake is true. Irrelevant otherwise. Default: []

  • maxfunctionlength (int): the maximum allowed length of a function. This is theoretically counting lines, but more closely resembles counting statements. For well-laid-out code it is usually within a line or two of being correct, and the skipped lines are inconsequential (closing braces/brackets, etc.). Default: 30

  • nostylechecks (bool): disable style and variable name checks. This means students can write pretty much any code that will compile, not just good code. Default: false.

  • nowall (bool): Remove the -Wall flag from the compiler flags. Default false.

  • nowerror (bool): Remove the -Werror flag from the compiler flags. Default false.

  • pointerregex (string): the regular expression that all pointer variable names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

  • proscribedconstructs (stringlist): a list of forbidden constructs (e.g. "goto", "for") that must not occur in the program.

  • proscribedfunctions (stringlist): a list of functions that must not be called. As of right now, this includes in testing code that would be inserted into main, so the test code is also not allowed to use proscribed functions.

  • proscribedsubstrings (stringlist): a list of strings that must not appear anywhere within the code, including in comments. Default: []

  • requiredconstructs (stringlist): a list of constructs (e.g. "while", "switch") that must be used in the program.

  • requiredfuncdecls (stringlist): a list of function names that must be defined in the program.

  • requiredsubstrings: this is either a list of strings that must appear somewhere in the students code. Or a list of json objects with the keys "string", "pattern" and "errormessage". Only one of "string" or "pattern" should be supplies. "String" corresponds to a string that must appear in the students code and "pattern" corresponds to a python regular expression that must match somewhere in the students code. "errormessage" is the feedback that will be given to students when they fail this on precheck.
  • showfeedbackwhenright: If true then if a student provides a valid solution then the student is presented with an option to see the question authors solution.
    Default: false

  • sourcefilename (string): the name given to the answer box contents when saving to a file. Default: student_answer.c.

  • std (string): Set the C standard. Default c99. 

  • stdinfromextra (bool): if true, standard input is taken from the extra template data of each test case, allowing the template to do a single compile and check of the submitted code, then execute the code once for each test case, using the extra template data as standard input. Otherwise, if standard input is supplied via the usual testcase form field, CodeRunner automatically runs the template once for each test, which is much slower. Default: false.

  • structregex (string): the regular expression that all struct names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

  • styleflags (stringlist): the style guidelines that must be followed for a successful submission. The flags will be passed as command-line arguments to a lightly patched version of astyle. Default: ["--style=1tbs", "--indent-labels"].

  • testisbash (bool): if true, the test code is interpreted as a bash command.

  • testshavemain (bool): if true, each test should contain the complete main function. A separate compile-and-run is required for each test in this situation.

  • timeout (int): number of seconds before a test is kicked off the CPU. Care must be needed here: the total time over all tests must be less than 30 seconds or the entire run will fail with a message like "Bad output from grader". Default: 5 seconds.

  • usemake (bool): true if make is to be used rather than gcc to compile and build the executable. Usually a Makefile will be supplied in conjunction with this parameter. See also the makeflags parameter. Default: false.

  • typeregex (string): the regular expression that all typedef'd names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

  • valgrind (bool): if true, the program is run using valgrind. Valgrind output is suppressed unless there are errors and/or memory leaks. Default: false.

  • validvariablenames (string): a list of variable names that are valid, but don't match the variableregex requirements. The names ['c', 'i', 'j', 'k', 'm', 'n', 's', 't', 'x', 'y', 'z'] are always allowed, optionally followed by a single digit - validvariablenames adds to that list. Also, for pointer variables, a preceding 'p' is allowed, e.g. pc1 is legitimate (as a pointer to a char). Default: []

  • variableregex (string): the regular expression that all variable names must match against. Default: '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$'

import subprocess import locale import json locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'C.UTF-8') subprocess.call(["unzip", "support.zip"], stdout=open('/dev/null', 'w')) from resulttable import sanitise STANDARD_INCLUDES = ['', '', '', '', '', '', ''] KNOWN_PARAMS = { 'abortonerror': True, 'allowglobals': False, 'allowmodulestatics': False, 'allowpositivereturn': False, 'allowstderr': False, 'arrayregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', 'checkheaders': True, 'checkalloc': False, 'checkfiles': False, 'checktemplateparams': True, 'constructlimits': {}, 'executablefilename': 'student_answer', 'extra': 'None', 'flags': ["-g", "-Wall", "-Werror"], 'functionregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', 'imagewidth': None, 'ignoreanswerbox': False, 'includes': [], 'includes': [], # Special case - STANDARD_INCLUDES get added in to whatever is given in template params 'includesource': [], 'isfunction': False, 'ldflags': ['-lm'], 'makeflags': [], 'maxfunctionlength': 30, 'maxoutputbytes': 10000, 'nostylechecks': False, 'pointerregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', 'proscribedconstructs': ["goto"], 'proscribedfunctions': [], 'proscribedsubstrings': [], 'requiredconstructs': [], 'requiredsubstrings': [], 'requiredfuncdecls': [], 'runtestssingly': False, 'showfeedbackwhenright': False, 'sourcefilename': 'student_answer.c', 'stdinfromextra': False, 'structregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', 'styleflags': ['--style=1tbs', '--indent-labels'], 'testisbash': False, 'testshavemain': False, 'timeout': 5, 'typeregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', 'usemake': False, 'valgrind': False, 'validvariablenames': [], 'variableregex': '[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,99}$', } class TestCase: def __init__(self, dict_rep): """Construct a testcase from a dictionary representation obtained via JSON""" self.testcode = dict_rep['testcode'] self.stdin = dict_rep['stdin'] self.expected = dict_rep['expected'] self.extra = dict_rep['extra'] self.display = dict_rep['display'] try: self.testtype = int(dict_rep['testtype']) except: self.testtype = 0 self.hiderestiffail = bool(int(dict_rep['hiderestiffail'])) self.useasexample = bool(int(dict_rep['useasexample'])) self.mark = float(dict_rep['mark']) # ================= CODE TO DO ALL TWIG PARAMETER PROCESSING =================== def process_template_params(): """Extract the template params into a global dictionary PARAMS""" global PARAMS PARAMS = json.loads("""{{ QUESTION.parameters | json_encode | e('py') }}""") checktemplateparams = PARAMS.get('checktemplateparams', True) if checktemplateparams: unknown_params = set(PARAMS.keys()) - set(KNOWN_PARAMS.keys()) filtered_params = [param for param in unknown_params if not param.startswith('_')] if filtered_params: print("Unexpected template parameter(s):", list(sorted(filtered_params))) unknown_params = set(PARAMS.keys()) - set(KNOWN_PARAMS.keys()) for param_name, default in KNOWN_PARAMS.items(): if param_name in PARAMS: param = PARAMS[param_name] if type(param) != type(default): print("Template parameter {} has wrong type (expected {})".format(param_name, type(default))) else: PARAMS[param_name] = default; if PARAMS['extra'] == 'stdin': PARAMS['stdinfromextra'] = True PARAMS['includes'] += STANDARD_INCLUDES def get_test_cases(): """Return an array of Test objects from the template parameter TESTCASES""" test_cases = [TestCase(test) for test in json.loads("""{{ TESTCASES | json_encode | e('py') }}""")] return test_cases def process_global_params(): """Plug the globals STUDENT_ANSWER, IS_PRECHECK and QUESTION_PRECHECK into the global PARAMS """ if PARAMS['ignoreanswerbox']: PARAMS['STUDENT_ANSWER'] = "" else: PARAMS['STUDENT_ANSWER'] = """{{ STUDENT_ANSWER | e('py') }}""".replace('\t', ' ') # Replace tabs with spaces. PARAMS['SEPARATOR'] = "##" PARAMS['IS_PRECHECK'] = "{{ IS_PRECHECK }}" == "1" PARAMS['QUESTION_PRECHECK'] = {{ QUESTION.precheck }} # Type of precheck: 0 = None, 1 = Empty etc PARAMS['ALL_OR_NOTHING'] = "{{ QUESTION.allornothing }}" == "1" # Whether or not all-or-nothing grading is being used with open("__author_solution.html") as file: PARAMS['FEEDBACK'] =file.read().strip() % """{{QUESTION.answer|e('html')|e('py')}}""" from ctester import CTester process_template_params() test_cases = get_test_cases() process_global_params() tester = CTester(PARAMS, test_cases) outcome = tester.test_code() if outcome['fraction'] == 1 and PARAMS['showfeedbackwhenright'] and PARAMS['FEEDBACK'] and not (PARAMS['IS_PRECHECK']): if 'epiloguehtml' in outcome: outcome['epiloguehtml'] += '
' else: outcome['epiloguehtml'] = '' if (PARAMS['STUDENT_ANSWER'].strip() == """{{ QUESTION.answer | e('py') }}""".strip()): mesg_model_student_match = "

Your answer is an exact match with the author's solution.

" PARAMS["FEEDBACK"] = mesg_model_student_match outcome['epiloguehtml'] += f'
{PARAMS["FEEDBACK"]}
' print(json.dumps(outcome))
